                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1070" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1070" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1070" type="surname" value="DOWNING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1070" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD DOWNING.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a surgeon. I was called to the deceased's home about nine o'clock on Saturday evening, the 22nd of Aug.—I found her up stairs—she complained of great thirst, constant vomiting, violent pain of the bowels, and involuntary diarrhoea—she did not complain of her throat—I felt her pulse, and found that the power of life was rapidly sinking—I asked her what she had taken, and I understood, I think, from Mrs. Bywater that she had taken some jalap—when I arrived at the house the prisoner sent the boy into the next-door neighbour, Mrs. Bywater—she acme in immediately, and went up stairs first, and I followed her—I did not learn from the deceased that she had taken anything—it was Mrs. Bywater, in her presence—I immediately gave her some brandy and water, and also requested some one to go to my house for some medicine, to lose no time; and I gave her some astringent medicine, as the diarrhoea was so severe—I considered from the symptoms, that it was an attack of cholera—I remained there some few minutes—I did not see her again—I was not sent for again—understand she died about one that morning—I saw the prisoner on the Sunday evening—I told him his wife was seriously ill, dangerously ill; and I would do all I possibly could for her—he did not make any reply—he said he would send for the medicine directly, and Mrs. Bywater said she would come for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he give you any reason to believe that his wife had taken arsenie or any poison whatever? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> None whatever—he heard what I said—he said nothing at all to me about the situation of his wife—he was down stairs when I saw him—I only saw him once—he opened the door to me, I think, when I went in—I waited while he sent next door for Mrs. Bywater—I should think I was alone with him, altogether, seven or eight minutes—I then west up stairs with Mrs. Bywater—when I came down again I found him down stairs, and then I said that his wife was seriously ill, in great danger—he said nothing to me about her, on either occasion—I examined the body after<lb></lb>wards—I took out the stomach, and gave it to Dr. Taylor—Mrs. Bywater applied to me on the following morning for a certificate, which I refused—I was the first person that opened the body—I had no doubt then from the appearances that presented themselves, that her death was caused by poison—I have no doubt of it now—the stomach was highly inflamed, and also the duo<lb></lb>denum—I did not examine the throat—there were appearances which justi<lb></lb>fied me in taking out the stomach, and submitting it to a chemical analysis.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you ask the prisoner any question as to what his wife had taken in the course of the day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, nor did I ask Mrs. By<lb></lb>water—the woman herself was rapidly sinking, she was hardly able to articu<lb></lb>late—I remained there seven or eight minutes, altogether—not less than that—I think it was seven minutes—I did not inquire what food she had taken that day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1071" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1071" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1071" type="surname" value="HUTCHINGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1071" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS HUTCHINGS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I went out in the morning with the beef to the baker's, in my old trowsers—I changed my clothes before dinner—I do not think it was long before—I do not think it was above half as hour—I went up into my own room to change them—I did not go to the drawer in which I had the arsenic—I had an opportunity then of seeing the outside of the drawer—the drawers were all in their places at that time—I am quite sure of that—I observed nothing like a breakage of my small drawer—it was not out in the room—I came down after I had changed my clothes—my father did not go up stairs to my room afterwards, before we sat down</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200181"></xptr>
               <p>to dinner, that I saw; I never saw him go up—he was not down stairs when I was changing my clothes—he was out—he came home while I was gone for the dinner—I found him at home when I returned—I did not go into my room again till tea-time—we dined between one and two—I do not think I stopped in the house longer than half an hour after dinner—when I left the house after dinner, my father was gone up stairs to lie down—my mother did not go up too—I do not think my mother went up at all before I left the house—I cannot say exactly how long before I left the house, my father had gone up stairs; but I do not think more than a quarter of an hour.</p>
               <p>
